# NumPy Lesson Structure

When generating NumPy learning materials, keep a strict hierarchy and continuity:
`Level -> Lessons -> Blocks`.

## Course structure policy

- A level may contain several lessons, split by subtopics.
- A lesson may contain several blocks, each block is one logical concept.
- Default recommendation:
  - 2-4 lessons per level
  - 3-6 blocks per lesson
- Do not put a whole level into one oversized lesson.
- Split into multiple lessons when topic depth, edge cases, or workload becomes too high.
- Each next lesson assumes successful completion of all previous lessons (global order).

## Naming and numbering convention

- Use global (continuous) lesson numbering across all levels; do not reset per level.
- Naming format for notebooks:
  - `lesson-XXX-l{level:02d}-{topic-slug}.ipynb`
  - `XXX` is 3-digit global lesson number: `001`, `002`, `003`, ...
- Store notebooks directly under learning NumPy directory:
  - `learning/numpy/lesson-XXX-l{level:02d}-{topic-slug}.ipynb`
- Keep `topic-slug` lowercase, ASCII, and hyphen-separated.
- Examples:
  - `learning/numpy/lesson-001-l01-array-basics.ipynb`
  - `learning/numpy/lesson-002-l01-shape-and-axis.ipynb`
  - `learning/numpy/lesson-003-l02-indexing-basics.ipynb`

## Required lesson flow

1. Lesson metadata: title, level, global lesson number, prerequisites, learning goals, estimated time.
2. 3-6 content blocks per lesson.
3. Each block must contain:
   - Theory (short, focused explanation)
   - Example (runnable NumPy code cell)
   - Practice tasks (immediately after example)

## Pedagogical structure standard (must match high-quality notebook style)

- Start each lesson with:
  - module title and short context
  - previous/next lesson links
  - explicit "what you will learn" list
- Each major section must include:
  - concept explanation
  - runnable demonstration
  - interpretation of results
  - edge-case warning(s) where relevant
- Include at least one "mental model" explanation per lesson
  - e.g., memory layout, indexing geometry, shape transitions
- Include a concise module cheat sheet near the end:
  - key APIs
  - key attributes
  - typical pitfalls
- End with explicit transition:
  - what is mastered now
  - what next lesson builds on

## API explanation quality gate

- Never present a list of new NumPy functions as raw code without explanation.
- For each new API in a block, provide:
  - what it does
  - minimal signature (short form)
  - key parameters (with meaning of each argument)
  - expected output (`shape`, `dtype`, typical values)
  - when to use it in practice
- Argument description is mandatory (no exceptions):
  - include parameter name
  - include allowed value/type expectations
  - include behavioral effect on output
- If an API has optional arguments that are frequently used (`dtype`, `axis`, `endpoint`, `base`, etc.), they must be explicitly documented.
- For foundational APIs, do NOT compress many methods into one short theory paragraph.
- Foundational API delivery format is mandatory:
  - dedicated theory mini-block per API
  - dedicated runnable demo cell per API
  - dedicated practice task per API
  - dedicated assert-based validation per API task
- If a block introduces more than 2 new APIs, split into micro-sections.
- After demo code, add short output interpretation in plain language.
- Add 1-2 verification checks (`assert`) that confirm the explained behavior.
- Tasks may only use APIs explicitly explained in the same block or earlier lessons.
- For each lesson, include a short "Coverage checklist" (introduced APIs vs expected APIs for this topic).
- Before finalizing a lesson, run a gap check against roadmap topics for this level and either:
  - include the missing important APIs, or
  - explicitly mark them as deferred to a specific next lesson.

## Academic completeness standard (mandatory)

- No "minimal" lesson versions are allowed.
- Each lesson must be sufficient for academic progression:
  - complete conceptual explanation
  - API semantics and boundaries
  - representative examples
  - practice that checks understanding, not copy-paste only
- Every lesson must end with:
  - coverage checklist
  - explicit list of deferred topics (if any) with target lesson ID
- A lesson is NOT complete if important APIs from its roadmap scope are missing without explicit defer note.

## Level 1 minimum API checklist

- Array creation/core constructors: `array`, `zeros`, `ones`, `full`, `empty`.
- Identity/diagonal basics: `eye`, `identity`, `diag`, `diagonal`.
- Range constructors: `arange`, `linspace`, `logspace`.
- Pattern-based constructors: `zeros_like`, `ones_like`, `full_like`, `fromfunction`.

## Foundational constructors depth requirement (Level 1)

- The following APIs are mandatory as standalone learning units in Lesson 001:
  - `array`
  - `zeros`, `ones`, `full`, `empty`
  - `eye`, `identity`
  - `diag`, `diagonal`
  - `arange`, `linspace`, `logspace`
  - `zeros_like`, `ones_like`, `full_like`, `fromfunction`
- "Standalone learning unit" means:
  - theory (purpose + signature + parameters + output expectations)
  - runnable example
  - hands-on task
  - assert check for task outcome

## Language policy

- All learner-facing content must be in Russian.
- This includes lesson metadata, theory, task statements, hints, recap, and section headings.
- Code identifiers and NumPy API names remain in original form (e.g., `reshape`, `dtype`, `np.mean`).

## Block dependency and sequencing

- Blocks are strictly sequential and cumulative.
- Hard tasks in block `N` may reuse concepts from blocks `1..N-1`.
- Do not introduce a new advanced concept in tasks before teaching it in theory/examples.

## Practice task rules

- Number and difficulty of tasks must be context-appropriate, not fixed per block.
- Allowed patterns include (examples): only easy tasks, several easy tasks, easy+medium, medium+hard.
- Use hard tasks only when topic depth justifies it.
- Include expected shape/output hints without giving full solution.
- Tasks must be result-oriented: describe target outcome/state first, not the exact code to type.
- Do not use copy-paste task wording like `Создай x = np.func(...)` as the main formulation.
- Preferred style: "получи массив/результат с такими свойствами" + "используй `<API>`".
- At least some tasks in each lesson should require combining current block material with prior lessons.
- Do not place all tasks in one large markdown block.
- Each task must be a separate mini-block: markdown task statement + dedicated code cell directly below it.
- Task statement format must include:
  - Goal
  - Input data or generation rule
  - Expected output constraints (`shape`, `dtype`, key conditions)
  - Optional restriction (e.g., no Python loops)
- Tasks in a block must rely only on concepts already explained in that block (and previously completed material). Do not require unseen APIs or concepts.
- Every task must have a dedicated validation cell with `assert` checks.
- Validation cells are mandatory; tasks without objective checks are not acceptable.
- In final lesson artifacts, do not leave unresolved placeholder-only solutions (e.g., TODO-only cells without checks and expected outcomes).

## Edge cases and pitfalls coverage

- Every lesson must include a dedicated edge-cases section for the topic.
- Must include at least 2 realistic pitfalls with demonstration code.
- Pitfalls should be executable and observable (not text-only), with brief fix guidance.

## Consistency and correctness checks

- Before finalizing lesson, verify that:
  - examples and comments are consistent
  - code outputs match stated expectations
  - no contradictory explanation remains after edits
- All code cells must be syntactically valid Python.
- Do not insert raw line breaks inside quoted string literals in code cells.
- For multiline print labels, use escaped newline sequences (`\\n`) inside strings.
- Run a preflight compile check for every code cell before finalizing the notebook.
- If a section is partially deferred, mark it explicitly in deferred topics with target lesson ID.

## Continuity requirements

- Every new block assumes previous blocks are completed.
- Every new lesson assumes previous lessons are completed.
- Start each lesson with a short prerequisite check list (2-4 quick checks).
- End each lesson with:
  - recap and readiness criteria for next lesson
  - one consolidated "Критерии самопроверки" section for the whole lesson
- Define lesson pass criteria (default):
  - all easy tasks completed
  - at least 70% of medium tasks completed
  - at least 1 hard task completed (if hard tasks exist)

## Notebook formatting

- Use clear Markdown headings for each block.
- Keep code cells executable top-to-bottom without hidden state.
- Prefer small, verifiable code examples over long scripts.
- If random is used, enforce reproducibility with `np.random.default_rng(seed)`.
- Include dedicated check cells with `assert` for key tasks.
